[2] Connecticut
Date: Wed 1 Nov 2006
From: Joe Dudley <jdudley@eaicorp.com>
Source: Hartford (CT) Courant [edited]
<http://www.courant.com/news/local/hc-ctoutbreak1101.artnov01,0,334796.story?coll=hc-headlines-local>

Connecticut health officials have identified 6 people who were
sickened by the same strain of salmonella that led to the temporary
closing of a popular Canton eatery early in October 2006, but who had
not eaten at the restaurant.
The cases are another piece of the puzzle in the outbreak, which
eventually sickened at least 172 people in 18 states, according to
CDC. Dr. Matthew Cartter, the state deputy epidemiologist, said 23
cases were traced to Margaritas restaurant.
11 people have been hospitalized in the outbreak, including 4 in
Connecticut. No deaths have been reported. State health officials are
working with the CDC to try to determine the source of the outbreak.
They believe the bacteria spread through produce, such as lettuce or tomatoes.
Health officials ordered Margaritas closed on 13 Oct 2006, and the
restaurant was thoroughly cleaned. Cartter said the 1st conference
call with other states and the CDC occurred on 19 Oct 2006, the day
Margaritas was cleared to reopen.
The 6 cases not associated with the restaurant are still being investigated.
Even though the cause has not been determined, Cartter said it
appears there is no current threat in the food distribution system
because the last case has been traced to food consumed on 6 Oct 2006.
"Whatever the source of the contamination was, it appears to be
something that happened and is over," he said.
[Byline: Mark Spencer]
--
Joseph P. Dudley, PhD
