[3] Kentucky
Date: Wed 1 Nov 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Louisville (KY) Courier-Journal [edited]
<http://www.courier-journal.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20061101/NEWS01/611010568/1008/NEWS01>

A salmonella outbreak possibly linked to produce has sickened 15
Kentuckians, one person in Indiana and at least 155 people in 17
other states in recent weeks.
In Kentucky, the outbreak began in Laurel and Whitley counties in
southeastern Kentucky, followed by cases in the Lexington-area
counties of Fayette and Scott, said Dr. Robert Brawley, chief of the
Communicable Disease Branch of the Kentucky Department of Public Health.
The Kentucky cases occurred in September 2006, Brawley said. Four
people were hospitalized, all from Laurel County, he said.
Kentucky epidemiologists have not identified a common source of the
state's cases, Brawley said.
Health officials estimate that more than 1.4 million cases of
salmonella infection occur in the United States each year, about 1.3
million of them from food.
[Byline: Patrick Howington]
